[2] Russian (Volgograd)
Date: Tue 3 Jan 2012
Sosurce: Komsomolskaya Pravda, Volgograd [In Russian, machine translation, edited]
http://volgograd.kp.ru/online/news/1053669


Measles outbreak in Volgograd continues
-----------------------------------
There have been 7 cases in just one day of the New Year holidays The measles epidemic began in Volgograd back in December [2011]. A few dozen peope are occupying hospital beds. In a few cases the infection was quite severe. All infected individuals have been admitted to the local infectious diseases hospital. However, the holiday period is not stemming the outbreak. During the 1st few days of the new year another 10 people have fallen ill. Four of 6 patients identified yesterday [2 Jan 2012] have been hospitalized. So Vogograd residents should be alert and if symptoms of fever and severe headache are experienced, you should immediately call the emergency number of the duty officer at he Volgograd region Rospotrebnadzor [Public Health Organisation].

Measles virus infection is transmitted by airborne droplets. And if you know someone infected, contact should be avoided. These symptoms of measles consist of swelling and redness of the face, runny nose, eye irritation, lacrimation, fever and hoarse cough. Measles is accompanied by development of a rash on the face, subsequently extending over the whole body.

A natural measles virus infection confers long-term immunity. Recurrent measles infections are rare and protective vaccination provides long-term immunity. The incubation period for measles 9-12 days.

(By Catherine Malinin)

